Liberation extension: building capacities for civilizational transition.

Copeland N(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of History, Virginia Polytechnic and State University, 431 Major 
Williams Hall (0117), 220 Stanger Street, Blacksburg, VA 24061 USA.

COVID 19 has exacerbated and underscored structural inequalities and endemic 
vulnerabilities in food, economic, and social systems, compounding concerns 
about environmental sustainability and racial and economic justice. Convergent 
crises have amplified a growing chorus of voices and movements calling for new 
thinking and new practices to adapt to these shifts, mitigate their impact, and 
address their root causes through far reaching changes in social and economic 
life and values, including breaking with the free market paradigm. In the face 
of a historic choice between transition or multiple systems collapse that deepen 
injustice and threaten planetary survival, I make the case for expanding on 
liberatory tendencies in Extension programs to build capacities for 
response-ability to transition toward more just and sustainable futures.

